    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_844310833" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/844310833" />
    <a title="Bithi" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/28028883-bithi"><img alt="Bithi" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1532003739p2/28028883.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/844310833?book_show_action=true">Feb 04, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bithi" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bithi" href="/user/show/28028883-bithi">Bithi</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer844310833" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12956500783408738500">This book is breath-taking in its suspense.<br/><br/>I am not sure if I should call the antagonist, Zobrist, a mad or futuristic person. Like all the antagonists of Brown&apos;s novels, he is apparently intelligent.<br/><br/>But, to quote Shakespeare - <i>There is method in madness.</i> (from <i>Hamlet</i>.<br/><br/>Even the author does not seem to portray the character of Zobrist as a cruel person like his other antagonists. Because, though Zobrist&apos;s solution is drastic, the issue of population increase in the world is very real.<br/><br/>In this book,</span>
  <span id="freeText12956500783408738500" style="display:none">This book is breath-taking in its suspense.<br /><br />I am not sure if I should call the antagonist, Zobrist, a mad or futuristic person. Like all the antagonists of Brown's novels, he is apparently intelligent.<br /><br />But, to quote Shakespeare - <i>There is method in madness.</i> (from <i>Hamlet</i>.<br /><br />Even the author does not seem to portray the character of Zobrist as a cruel person like his other antagonists. Because, though Zobrist's solution is drastic, the issue of population increase in the world is very real.<br /><br />In this book, the hero and the villain are the same person.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12956500783408738500" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


